13 mistakes that will hurt your career:
 
(And how to fix them fast)
 
Thanks to my friend George Stern for this one!
 
1. Blind Loyalty
↳Staying in a job because it's easy or you're loyal, even if they might not be loyal in return
↳Fix: Regularly assess whether your company values you and your role challenges you; if not, explore other options
 
2. Self-Doubt
↳Imposter syndrome can keep you from opportunities you're qualified for
↳Fix: Keep a success journal, challenge self-doubt with evidence, and remember that growth requires learning
 
3. Invisible Effort
↳Working hard isn't enough - you need visibility and strategic relationships too
↳Fix: Speak up in meetings, document and update your manager on accomplishments, and build relationships
 
4. Outdated Skills
↳If you stop learning, you become less valuable in the job market over time
↳Fix: Take online courses, earn certifications, and follow industry trends to stay competitive
 
5. No Network
↳Career growth often depends as much or more on who you know than what you know
↳Fix: Set a goal to reach out to two new contacts per month and reconnect with former colleagues
 
6. Avoiding Feedback
↳Feedback can be scary, but without it, you won't know what's holding you back
↳Fix: Schedule regular check-ins with your manager and ask, "What's one thing I could improve?"
 
7. No Negotiation
↳If you never negotiate, you're leaving money, promotions, or opportunities on the table
↳Fix: Practice negotiation conversations, and learn to ask for what you want in a professional way
 
8. Risk Avoidance
↳Growth comes from challenges - staying safe can limit your potential
↳Fix: Take on stretch projects and volunteer for cross-function work with new people
 
9. Burned Bridges
↳How you leave a company matters - future opportunities can depend on your reputation
↳Fix: Maintain professionalism in all exits, no matter the circumstances, and apologise when necessary
 
10. Weak Branding
↳Your reputation online and offline shapes how people perceive your expertise
↳Fix: Build your personal brand, posting insights here on LinkedIn and contributing to industry discussions
 
11. Health Sacrifice
↳Burnout and poor health will set you back more than taking care of yourself
↳Fix: Prioritise sleep, exercise, and stress management, and remember that rest makes you MORE productive not less
 
12. Lack of Goals
↳Without direction, you risk wasting years in roles that don't serve you
↳Fix: Define short-term and long-term goals, then reverse-engineer a plan to achieve them
 
13. No Backup
↳Leaving on impulse can leave you financially and professionally vulnerable
↳Fix: Before quitting, secure another job, ensure financial stability, or have a well-thought-out strategy
 
Your career will have enough challenges.
 
Don’t let yourself be one of them.
 
Do you agree?

How you spend your time defines who you will become.

Here are 10 ways to own your time in 2025 ⬇️

Proper time management should never be underestimated. 

Once you start organising your time, you can: 

✅ Become more productive and effective. 
✅ Become better at prioritisation.
✅ Better work-life balance.   
✅ Better fulfilment. 

Not managing your time properly can have the opposite effect: 

You risk becoming overwhelmed, unhappy, and unproductive. 

For every distraction, it takes around 23 minutes to refocus.  
That could mean hours of lost productivity every day. 

That's why efficient time management is the key to progress.

These 10 methods will allow you to own your time in 2025:

1. Oliver Burkeman's 3/3/3 Method 🔢
↳ Commit to 3 hours of deep work on crucial tasks. 
↳ Spend 3 hours on quick, urgent tasks and finish with 3 admin items. 

2. The Eisenhower Matrix ⊹
↳ Figure out when to delegate and when to say ‘no’. 
↳ Prioritise important tasks ahead of unimportant and non-urgent ones.

3. Eliminate Multitasking 🤹‍♂️
↳ Maximise brain function by focusing on one thing at a time. 
↳ Concentrate on 1 task during a deep work session. 

4. Digital Detox 📱
↳ Schedule a regular time to spend away from any digital devices. 
↳ Return to work with improved mental clarity and productivity. 

5. Biological Scheduling 🧬
↳ Map your natural energy levels to see when you're most productive. 
↳ Plan to complete important tasks during high energy level moments.  

6. Get Things Done Rule 💪
↳ Go over your open tasks and prioritise based on importance. 
↳ Revisit and reflect on your to-do list after each task. 

7. Break Tasks Down 👊
↳ Break down complex tasks into smaller, more manageable parts. 
↳ Schedule the hardest parts for when you're at peak productivity. 

8. AI Tools 🤖
↳ Delegate smaller, unimportant tasks to an AI-powered scheduling tool. 
↳ Reduce the cognitive load of planning and executing small tasks. 

9. Seinfeld Strategy ☄️
↳ Turn goals into daily habits to better manage your time.  
↳ Maintain the daily streak as long as you can and never take 2 days off.

10. The 2-Minute Rule ⏱️
↳ Any task that takes less than two minutes should be done immediately. 
↳ This will stop procrastination and overthinking about small tasks. 

People say "time is money."

But the truth is, time is everything. 

Which time management method is your favourite?

Here’s the painfully honest, slightly embarrassing, and ultimately triumphant story of how S.A.D. (Sales Are Dope) went from a silly social media sketch to... Well, a movie on Amazon.

2013 - Posted first ever Corp Bro video

2017 - Coined the acronym S.A.D.N.E.S.S. (Sales Are Dope Never Ever Stop Selling) and started writing a Corporate Bro TV pilot 

2019 - Shot the self-financed pilot down in LA - It was SO BAD. Fun fact: We fired our director after day 1 and also somehow* cast literal porn-stars as extras…

Early 2020 - Released the pilot during the heart of the pandemic via a Youtube premiere with 3,000 people watching it together virtually. 

2020-2021 - Wrote and wrote and wrote and finally finished a fully reworked season of SAD

2022 - Raised/financed ~$500k and shot the 8 episode web series (shoutout Bravado & Scratchpad)

2023 - Released the full series on Youtube and hosted a premiere in SF

2024 - Amazon asked if we’d considered a film-cut version of SAD (luckily we had)

2025 - SAD gets picked up on Amazon as a movie!

Here's the thing. We never did this for money (SAD is still deep in the red). We never even had a proper marketing plan (oops). We just had this need in our souls to create something authentic about the insanity and pain of working in Sales. And while we didn't make the next Office Space or Glengarry Glen Ross, we made SOMETHING.

And now? It's a real movie. Still feels surreal typing that.

To everyone who supported this journey, many of you right here on Linkedin- appreciate ya. To Ben who's been there since day one - couldn’t have done it without you.

Biggest lesson? Don't wait for permission. Don't wait for perfect conditions. Just make the thing you want to make.

Because sometimes that one-minute video turns into a movie on Amazon.

Ever logged in for “5 minutes” and lost an hour?

I did this more often than I’d like to admit...

So, I had to set boundaries for LinkedIn, too.
1 hack helped me manage my time here.

Time blocking. (Here's my version of it...)

Every time you log in, set a 10-minute timer.
It’s enough time to scroll, comment, and reply.

But it’s not enough to suck you into the loop.

The only exception you should make?
The Golden Hour. (Engagement matters.)

And if LinkedIn starts to feel unmanageable? 

Slow down. Reflect on the time spent here.
Consistency is important, yes, but so is your time.

The truth is, LinkedIn reach easily comes back.
Your time and energy? Not that easy.

Protect those at any cost.

And remember, it’s okay to take a break.

Set your own pace here.

It’s your time and energy after all.
